\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Vehicular edge computing (VEC) is a promising technology to support real-time vehicular applications, where vehicles offload intensive computation tasks to the nearby VEC server for processing. However, the traditional VEC that relies on single communication technology cannot well meet the communication requirement for task offloading, thus the heterogeneous VEC integrating the advantages of dedicated short-range communications (DSRC), millimeter-wave (mmWave) and cellular-based vehicle to infrastructure (C-V2I) is introduced to enhance the communication capacity. The communication resource allocation and computation resource allocation may significantly  impact the ultra-reliable low-latency communication (URLLC) performance and the VEC system utility, in this case, how to do the resource allocations is becoming necessary. In this paper, we consider a heterogeneous VEC with multiple communication technologies and various types of tasks, and propose an effective resource allocation policy to minimize the system utility while satisfying the URLLC requirement. We first formulate an optimization problem
to minimize the system utility under the URLLC constraint which modeled by the moment
generating function (MGF)-based stochastic network calculus (SNC), then we present a Lyapunov-Guide deep reinforcement learning (DRL) method to convert and solve the optimization problem. Extensive simulation experiments illustrate that the proposed resource allocation approach is effective.


%We analyze the offloading delay upper bound of heterogeneous communication technologies and demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed offloading policy in the heterogeneous VEC by giving simualtion results.

%To obtain the tractable URLLC constraint we adpot the stochastic network calculus theory to derive the offloading delay upper bound through three commnucation technologies, and resort Lyapunov optimization to transform the long-term ultra reliability constraint into an short-time decision problem. The soft actor-critic (SAC) is adopted to learn the optimal offloading policy based on the deep reinforcement learning (DRL) framework.


%???Vehicular edge computing (VEC) is a promising paradigm to alleviate the computation burdens for vehicular user (VU). In the VEC system, VUs can push the compuation-thirsty tasks to nearby server to enhance the Quality of Sevice (QoS). However, the surging data poses a great threat to the ultra-relibale low-latency (URLLC) for the emerging 5G applications. In addtion, depending on a single communication technology already unable to accommodate the requirements of task soffloading at the vehicular computing edge. In this paper, we first propse a vehicle tasks offloading system with mmWave, dsrc and C-V2I communication technologies subject to the URLLC constraint which is characterized in terms of queuing long-term average length. Then, stochastic network caculus theory is adopted to derive the system delay for task offloading with respect to each communication technique so as to guarantee the task transmission within the required latency. Accordingly, we formulate an optimization problem to maximize the long-term utility of the vehicle traffic edge computing network. Lypunuov optimization is resorted to simplify this long-term stochastic problem with URLLC constraints. Ultimately, this paper constructs a learning DRL-based framework for formulating server-side CPU resource allocation policy and VUs-side task offloading communication technologies selection policy. The soft actor-critic (SAC) algorithm is adopted to learn the optimal policy based on the DRL framework. Finally, we demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed scheme in the vehicular edge computing network by giving numerical results.
\end{abstract}
\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Heterogeneous, Vehicular edge computing, URLLC, Resource allocation
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

%\IEEEPARstart{W}{ith} the rapid \hl{advancement} of the Internet of Vehicles (IoV) in the coming 5G Era, the demands of the vehicular user (VUs) for the immersive Quality of Experience (QoE) and the computing-intensive services, such as the online 3D game, augmented and virtual reality (AR/VR), video or other interactive applications\cite{ref1}, \hl{imposing stringent requirements on the IoV.} On top of that there will be 1GB of data per second for an autonomous vehicle generated by the high-definition resolution cameras LiDARS, HD maps with high rate and other on-board sensors \cite{ref2,ref3}. It is an enormous pressure for a vehicle with insufficient computing \hl{and storing } capabilities to execute these computing-thirsty tasks.

\IEEEPARstart{W}{ith} the coming of the fifth generation (5G) era, the demands of the real-time vehicular applications such as the online three-dimensional (3D) game, augmented/virtual reality (AR/VR) as well as high definition video are increasing\cite{ref1}. These applications need the supports of large amount of data collected by the high definition (HD) resolution cameras, light detection and ranging (LiDAR) and HD maps with high rate \cite{ref2}. On one hand, such large amount of data may result in intensive computation tasks to be processed in time. However, the computation and storage capability of vehicles are usually insufficient, how to deal with the computing-thirsty tasks is becoming a great challenge. On the other hand, vehicular edge computing (VEC) is regarded as a promising paradigm to support the real-time vehicular applications, where a VEC server with sufficient computation and storage  capability is deployed in close proximity to the vehicles at roadside. In this case, vehicles first offload tasks to the VEC server in their vicinity for processing, then the VEC server returns the processed results to the vehicles, and the real-time vehicular applications may be perfectly supported\cite{ref5, 2022Zhao, 2022Zhu}.

%\hl{It is an enormous pressure for a vehicle with insufficient computing resources and storing capabilities to process these computing-thirsty data. Vehicular edge compution (VEC) is regarded as a promising paradigm to support real-time applications, where a VEC server is deployed in close proximity to the vehilces at roadside, VUs first can cache applications on the vehicle, then the vehicle will offload applications to the VEC server in their vicinity for processing, finally the VEC server returns the processed applications back to the vehicle}\cite{ref4,ref5}.

Up to now, there are three major communication technologies in VEC to support task offloading, i.e., dedicated short range communications (DSRC), cellular-based vehicle to infrastructure (C-V2I) and millimeter-wave (mmWave). DSRC is a short-range communication technology, which operates from 5.85GHz to 5.92GHz band based on the 802.11p standard\cite{ref8,2011Kenney}, but it exhibits poor performance in the case of high vehicle density \cite{2012Han}. C-V2I works with the cellular licensed spectrum to provide wide geographical coverage and high data rate services \cite{2017wang,ref9}, but it is not capable to support the real-time information exchange with very high data rate \cite{ref9,ref10,ref11}. mmWave is the wireless communication technology which works on the underutilized spectrum (i.e., 3-300Hz) to achieve multi-gigabit data rate for autonomous driving. However, the propagation loss of mmWave channel is high and obstructions will lead to high attenuation of mmWave channel \cite{ref12,ref13,ref14,ref15}. As known, the traditional VEC relying on single communication technology cannot meet the communication requirement for task offloading with very high data rate. Thus, the heterogeneous VEC integrating the advantages of the three communications will have the great potential to enhance the communication capability to provide such kinds of services.
%Moreover, vehicles in the heterogeneous VEC usually generate various types of tasks with heterogeneous quality of service (QoS) requirements, which require the VEC server associated with different central processing unit (CPU) frequencies.


Ultra-reliable low-latency communication (URLLC) at VEC should satisfy the basic performance requirements, i.e., low latency between 10-100ms and store 1000 times higher data volumes compared with 4G systems\cite{2020Chen,2020WQ}. The problem is naturally raised. That is how to effectively utilize the limited communication resource and computation resource. In fact, the system utility including the fees charged for communications and energy consumed by the CPU of the VEC server is also very important, which may affect the system plan and design. For the limited communication and computation resources in the heterogeneous VEC, the resource allocation policy including the partition proportion of the three communication technologies to offload each type of tasks, and CPU frequency allocated to process each type of tasks, will significantly impact the URLLC and system utility. Meanwhile, the communication and computation resource allocation policy are also coupled with each other. In addition, the ultra reliability of the VEC server is difficult to be satisfied due to its long-term time-average characteristic. To the best of our knowledge, no works have studied how to guarantee the URLLC requirement in the heterogeneous VEC.

%Specifically, different communication allocation policies will result in the different offloading delays and communication fees, and different computation allocation policies will affect offloading delay, ultra reliability of the VEC server and the energy consumption.

%It is necessary to determine the communication allocation policy, i.e., the percentages of each type tasks to be offloaded by three communication technologies, and the CPU frequency allocation policy, i.e., the percentages of the CPU frequency to be allocated for each type tasks.





%\hl{In the heterogeneous VEC, various types tasks have heterogeneous quality of sevice (QoS) requirements. Especially in the 5G era,  VUs are intended for computation-intensive and high QoS applications, which various applications need various computing resources and require different maximum latency.}



