%However, solving such resources allocating problems typically requires prohibitively high computational complexity especially in the large-scale vehicular networks\cite{2021Bi}. Besides, the problems are generally non-convex and thorny optimization affected by the stochastic task arrivals and the time-varying channels conditon\cite{ref16,ref17,ref18,ref19}. The recent development of data-driven Deep reinforcement learning (DRL) provides a promising alternative to tackle the online vehicular computation offloading problem, which is able to adjust the offloading policies and resources alloactions without requiring any prior knowledge of the vehicular environment to achieve a best long-term goal. To the best of our knowledge, no works focused on the the low offloading latency of the tasks and the stability of the queues in the edge node in the VEC scenario to jointly optimize heterogeneous communication offloading policies, as well as the computational resources allocations made by the VEC server, which motivates us to conduct this work.


%\hl{In this paper, we propose a Deep Reinforcement Soft Actor Critic (SAC) algorithm to maximize the system utility of the heterogeneous vehicular edge computing under URLLC contraints. First, we will propose an optimization problem which aims to minimize the utility of the system on condition of URLLC. Then by leveraging stochastic network calculus (SNC) theory, we can derive the delay upper bound of offloading tasks, including of the delay of offloading tasks includes the transmission delay and  the delay of processing tasks by the VEC server. Next, we resort to the Lyapunov optimization to transform the ultra reliability constraint into an short-term decision problem. Finally, the DRL framework is formulated and the SAC is adopted to obtain the optimal policy which includes the offloading policy of heterogeneous communication and the allocaion of computing resources.}
In this paper, we propose a resource allocation policy to minimize the system utility while guaranteeing the URLLC requirement in the heterogeneous VEC\footnote{The source code has been released at:  https://github.com/qiongwu86/URLLC-Awared-Resource-Allocation-for-Heterogeneous-Vehicular-Edge-Computing}. The major contributions of this paper are summarized as follows:

\begin{itemize}
	\item{An optimization problem is formulated. Since the stochastic network calculus (SNC) serves as a vital tool that effectively accommodates communication aspects such as transmission, interference, and collisions, offering a comprehensive model of the communication process, we first adopt a moment generating function (MGF)-based SNC to construct the network service of mmWave, DSRC and C-V2I. Then, the system utility consisting of the communication utility and computation utility is characterized with an explicit form. Later on, we formulate an optimization problem to minimize the system utility while meeting URLLC requirement. }
	
	\item{The SNC-based optimization problem introduces the long-term constraints and complex interactions, which make it extremely difficult to address the optimization problem using the traditional optimization methods. To overcome the challenges, we propose a Lyapunov-Guided DRL method to reformulate and solve the optimization problem. Specifically, we adopt the Lyapunov optimization to convert the long-term ultra reliability constraint into a short-term constraint. Based on the results, we reformulate the optimization problem based on the short-term constraint and make it as a tractable optimization problem.}
	
	\item{Deep reinforcement learning (DRL) emerges as a potent and efficient solution for resource allocation and offloading in vehicular networks due to its rapid decision-making capabilities and adaptability to dynamic conditions, highlighting its superiority over traditional methods and indicating its potential for further applications in this domain. Hence, we present a deep learning solution. We design a DRL framework including the state, action and reward and adopt the soft actor-critic (SAC) algorithm to learn the optimal resource allocation policy.}
\end{itemize}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section II reviews the related work. Section III introduces the system model which includes the data arrival model, network service model and computing service model, then we formulate the URRLC constraint and the system utility, and then formulate the optimization problem. In Section IV we convert the ultra reliability constraint to be the short term constraint. We then reformulate the optimization problem. Then we present the DRL based solution. Various simulation results are shown to demonstrate the performance of our proposed VEC system in Section \ref{simulation_chapter}. The conclusions are drawed in Section \ref{conclusion_chapter}.
\section{Related work}
In this section, we first review the related works on URLLC of the tasks offloading in VEC, then survey the existing works on heterogeneous vehicular networks (HetVNETs).
\subsection{URLLC in VEC}

In recent years, there are many works studied the URLLC in VEC.
% In \cite{2019Yang}, Yang \emph{et al.} analyzed the lower bound of spectral efficiency for URLLCs and security metric, and a secure caching placement and delivery algorithm was adopted to minimize the maximum vulnerability among all vehicular users and significantly improved the performance of security for the VEC URLLC system. In \cite{2021Hao}, Hao \emph{et al.} studied the deployment of vehicle tasks under 5G VEC networks and the allocation of URLLC resources,  a deep reinforcement learning algorithm was employed to solve the URLLC resource slicing and scheduling optimization problem. In \cite{2021Liao}, Liao \emph{et al.} developed a novel task offloading framework for air-ground integrated VEC, they modelled the long-term URLLC constraints by putting a probabilistic requirement on the extreme queue lengh and a high-order statistical requirement on the excess backlog, an intent-aware upper condifence bound algotithm was proposed to maximize the weighted sum of QoE and URLLC constraints. In \cite{2020YangHao}, Yang \emph{et al.} investigated the frame design and resource allocation for an urban V2V URLLC system, where two low-complexity policies were proposed to achieve the optimal frame design and resource allocation, while guaranteeing the URLLC requirements of V2V pairs and the signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio. In \cite{2019Guo}, Guo \emph{et al.} performed spectrum and power allocation to maximize the sum ergodic capacity of vehicle-to-infrastructure (V2I) links while guaranteeing the LVP for vehicle-to-vehicle (V2V) links, the URLLC constraint were explicitly expressed by using the effective capacity theory. In \cite{ref25}, Chao \emph{et al.} investigated a multi-user tasks offloading in the vehicular network by applying reinforcement learning Q-learning to maximize the output under the condition of URLLC contraints, where the URLLC constraints are defined as the extreme case of queue length with a specified delay bound violation. However, these works did not consider the heterogeneous communication technologies in the VEC.
%In \cite{2021Pan}, Pan \emph{et al.} characterized URLLC in terms of queuing delay bound violation and excess backlogs, then proposed a task offloading algorithm based on DRL to maximize the throughput of the vehicular users (VUs) while satisfying the URLLC constraints.
In \cite{2022Pan}, Pan \emph{et al.} established the URLLC constraint based on the extreme value theory, where the Lyapunov optimization was employed to decompose the task offloading and computation optimization, while considering the long-term URLLC constraints to present an asynchronous federated DQN-based algorithm to maximize the throughput. In \cite{2021Liao}, Liao \emph{et al.} developed a novel task offloading framework for the air-ground integrated VEC. They modeled the long-term URLLC constraints by putting a probabilistic requirement on the extreme queue length and a high-order statistical requirement on the excess backlog, and proposed an intent-aware upper confidence bound algorithm to maximize the constraints including the quality of service (QoS) and URLLC. In \cite{2020Batewela}, Batewela \emph{et al.} studied an URLLC communication problem for VEC, where the risk-sensitive notion was leveraged to define a reliability metric, and proposed the joint utility and policy estimation-based learning algorithm to minimize the end-to-end task offloading delay of each vehicle. In \cite{2021Cui}, Cui \emph{et al.} combined communication and computation resource allocation to reduce the total system cost consisting of latency and reliability, where a multi-objective reinforcement learning policy was adopted to approach the optimal solution in the internet of vehicles (IoV) edge computing networks. In \cite{2021Zhu}, Zhu \emph{et al.} characterized the reliability of the transmission stage in the finite blocklength regime and investigated the queue length violation in the computation stage based on the extreme value theory, where deep deterministic policy gradient (DDPG) was adopted to learn the optimal dynamic offloading policy. However, these works have not considered the heterogeneous wireless technologies to support the vehicular networks.
%In, xxx employed ... to ..., where ... was adopted to ...
%In, xxx considered ... for ..., where ... was adopted to .... by..
%In, xxx focused on .... to ...., as well as....
%In, xxx studied ... to.....

\subsection{Heterogeneous Vehicular Networks}
Some works have recently investigated the performance of vehicular networks by integrating various communication technologies. In \cite{ref2}, Xiong \emph{et al.} proposed a task offloading framework in HetVNETs by integrating DSRC, C-V2X and mmWave communication technologies. In \cite{ref8}, Zheng \emph{et al.} provided a comprehensive survey on advanced techniques applied to the vehicular networks, and proposed a HetVNET where cellular communication technologies were integrated with DSRC to provide a potential solution to meet the communication requirements of the intelligent transportation system. In \cite{2021Posner}, Posner \emph{et al.} investigated a federated vehicular network to support computation intensive applications such as distributed machine learning and federated learning by utilizing both DSRC and mmWave. In \cite{2022Zhang}, Zhang \emph{et al.} proposed a distributed message dissemination scheme for mmWave vehicle-to-vehicle (V2V) communications, where each vehicle was equipped with the two communication interfaces including the DSRC interface and mmWave interface. The DSRC interface was adopted to exchange management information while mmWave interface was responsible for realizing the directed massive messages distribution. In \cite{2018Sheng}, Sheng \emph{et al.} proposed an intelligent 5G heterogeneous wireless network architecture including a Q-learning based DSRC and mmWave to support V2V and vehicle to infrastructure (V2I) communications, respectively. This network architecture provided an optimal vertical handoff decision among other cross-layer management functions to coordinate network selection (NS). In \cite{2022Ming}, Ming \emph{et al.} proposed a hybrid V2V communication selection policy based on the evolutionary game, where vehicles could select the communications mode (i.e., DSRC or long term evolution-based vehicle to everything (LTE-V2X) mode 4) to improve the flexibility of packet transmissions. However, these works have not considered the different types of tasks and the URLLC requirement in the vehicular network.

As mentioned above, no work investigated the resource allocation problem in the heterogeneous VEC with multiple communications technologies to guarantee the URLLC requirement.
%However, these works have not considered the different types of tasks and the URLLC requirement in the vehicular network. Some works have considered the various task requirements in  the tasks offloading of VEC. In \cite{2022Lin}, Lin \emph{et al.} considered the different tasks requiring various computation resources and formulated an online vehicular task offloading problem to minimize the total offloading energy while guaranteeing the offloading delay of each task. In \cite{2020Hui}, Hui \emph{et al.} considered different tasks requiring various computing resources, and proposed a game theoretic scheme for vehicular task offloading to facilitate the computing services in 5G heterogeneous networks. In \cite{2021Lakhan}, Lakhan \emph{et al.} considered the heterogeneous CPU requirements and deadline of various tasks to formulate multi-side task offloading and scheduling problem, and designed a blockchain-enabled and mobility-aware scheme to minimize communication cost and computation cost. In \cite{2020Dai}, Dai \emph{et al.} considered the different types of tasks which require various computation resources and the upper delay bounds, and proposed an edge intelligence empowered 5G beyond network to optimize computation offloading. In \cite{2020Wang}, Wang \emph{et al.} proposed a DRL-based computation migration and resource allocation (RLCMRA) scheme to minimize the total cost in the 5G-enabled vehicular networks including the delay cost, energy computation cost and bandwidth cost. They considered heterogeneous tasks requiring different CPU frequency and execution delay. In \cite{2021Peng}, Peng \emph{et al.} formulated the resource allocation at VEC server as a distributive optimization problem to maximize the number of offloaded tasks while satisfying their heterogeneous QoS requirements, and then solved it based on a multi-agent deep deterministic policy gradient (MADDPG)-based method. However, these works only adopted single communication technology and have not considered the ULRRC in VEC.



