%In\cite{ref20}, Mao \emph{et al.} minimized the average power consumption by jointly allocating the communication, the CPU frequency and the transmission power, and took Liapunov's approach to achieve buffer stabilization. You \emph{et al.} in \cite{ref21} investigated multi-user mobile edge computing offloading based on TDMA and OFDMA, respectively, by combining resource allocation and offloading policies to minimize weighted user energy consumption while satisfying latency requirements. The authors in \cite{ref22} considered the impact of time-varying fading channel on the task offloading policies and maximized the network utility viewd as the offloading task number to the VEC server while satisfying the latency requirements of the task. In \cite{ref23}, Du \emph{et al.} studied dual-side maximum utility optimization for smart vehicular terminals (VTs) as well as the MEC server resource allocation, VTs needed to pay the MEC server for the communication transmission and task processing, and ultimately by leveraging Lyapunov optimization to obtain the most optimal task offloading policy and the local CPU frequency resource allocation for VTs as well as the optimal 802.22 communication burst resource assignment and the optimal transmit power control for the server, while controlling the queue stability of VTs and servers. But the above work were done by ensuring or optimizing the latency and stability requirements set for task offloading, without taking into account the extreme situations that would lead to severe performance fluctuations.




%Liu \emph{et al.} in \cite{ref24} considered two heterogeneous offloading policies, where tasks generated by vehicles can be offloaded to other vehicles or to cloud servers via RSU, min-plus algebra was adapted to abstract the two-hop link and the delay upper bound was derived based on the martingale theory, this paper achieved the minimization of the overall system delay violation probalility under the constraint that the generated tasks are within the network available off-loading capacity. In \cite{ref25}, Chao \emph{et al.}  investigated a multi-user VEC task offloading by applying reinforcement learning Q-learning to maximize the throughput under the condition of meeting URLLC contraints, defining the extreme case of queue length with a specified delay bound violation. The authors in \cite{ref7} constructed a vehicle network network-wide power minimization problem while maintaining an extremely small probability event that the queue length exceeds a predefined threshold, where the threshold of the queue length was derived by means of extreme value theory. With the development of artificial intelligence, reinforcement learning has been widely applied to VEC for solving resource allocation in task offloading problems. Yi \emph{et al.} explored a vehicle edge computing network architecture in which the vehicles were regarded as the mobile edge-servers to handle the tasks offloaded from other vehicles and employed the Q-learning based method and the DRL based method to maximize the utility subject to the latency requirement, whose utility was calculated as the cost of communication and computation utilized by the vehicle in \cite{ref26}.


