Consider the heterogeneous VEC network where vehicles adopt three kinds of communication technologies, i.e., C-V2I, DSRC and mmWave, denoted by the set $\mathcal{G} = \left\{mmw,dsrc,cv2i\right\}$, to offload $N$ types of tasks, here the set of task types is denoted by $\mathcal{N} =\ \left\{1,2,\cdots,N \right\}$. The VEC consists of vehicles, road side units (RSUs), a base station (BS) and a VEC server. The VEC server is connected with the BS and RSUs through wired link.
%All vehicles are driving in the coverage area of the BS and each vehicle is covered by at least one RSU.
The vehicles within the coverage of BS and RSU offload tasks to the BS and RSU, which will forward the tasks to the server for processing.
The server has $N$ queues. It receives the tasks from the vehicles and stores them in dedicated queues before tasks are processed.
In addition, it is equipped with $N_{E}$ CPU cores and the total CPU frequency of all CPU cores is $f_{E}$ cycles per second. The offloading process is divided into $T$ discrete time slots with the equal duration $\varDelta t$.
In the beginning of the each time slot $t$, each vehicle randomly generates one type  tasks, and the size of the each type of tasks arriving to the queues is $a_{i}(t) = n_{i} d_{i} $, where $n_{i}$ is the number of the tasks following the Poisson distribution with arrival rate $\lambda_{i}$, and $d_{i}$ is the constant size of the tasks.
Then the VEC server makes the communication resource allocation, i.e., deciding the partition proportion of the three communication technologies to offload each type $i$ of tasks,  denoted as $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t)$, $\varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t)$  and $\varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t)$, respectively, and the computation resource allocation, i.e., allocating the CPU frequency to process each type $i$ of tasks, denoted as $\alpha_{i}(t)$. After that, the vehicles offload tasks according to the adopted communication allocation policy. That is, as C-V2I can provide wide coverage while DSRC and mmWave only communicate over short distance, thus the $i$th type of tasks are transmitted to the BS by C-V2I with proportion $\varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t)$ and transmitted to the RSUs which are deployed in the vicinity of vehicles by DSRC or mmWave with proportions $\varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t)$ and $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t)$, respectively. Afterwards, the BS or RSUs forward tasks of type $i$ to queue $i$ of the VEC server and allocate $\alpha_{i}(t)$ of the total CPU frequency to process the tasks. Once the VEC server finishes the tasks, it will feedback the output results to the corresponding vehicles. Due to the fact that the resulting output data size of tasks is normally much smaller than the input one, the latency caused by downlink transmission are neglected. In addition, the transmission rate  of wired link is relatively large\cite{ref7}, the delay at wired link is not considered in this paper. Thus the delay of offloading tasks we consider is composed of the communication time and task processing time. The heterogeneous VEC scenario is shown in Fig. \ref{fig_1}.

%Next we will introduce the data arrival model, queue model, network service model and computing service model, respectively.

%The main notations in the paper are listed as Table \ref{tab1}.



%\hl{A complete offloading process consists of offloading tasks to the BS or RSUs, processing tasks by the VEC server, and returning results back to vehicles.}
%The bandwidth of the wired link is large enough so that we ignore the transmission time from RSU to BS.


%adopt the DSRC to offload the tasks to the BS or adopt the DSRC or mmWave to offload the tasks to the RSUs, then the BS or RSUs forwards the tasks to the VEC server for processing. The VEC caches the tasks needs to be processed in its cache queues.

%and caches the tasks needs to be calculated in its cache queues. The vehicles on the road generate $N$-types tasks and offload the tasks to the BS, then the BS forwards the tasks to the VEC server for processing.

%The VEC framework we put forward is shown as Fig. \ref{fig_1}, which consists of the vehicles, road side units (RSUs), the base station (BS) and the VEC server which is deployed to the BS. The VEC server with the queues caches the tasks which need to be calculated. The $N$-types tasks will be generated by the vehicles in the road. In this paper, we assume that the tasks will be all offloaded to the VEC server to be processed. Vehicles can offload the tasks to the RSUs by the DSRC or mmWave communications and then the tasks will be tranferred to the queues of the VEC server by the wired link, the bandwidth of the wired link is large enough so that we ignore the transmission time from RSU to BS. The vehicles also can offload the tasks directly to the BS by the celluar communication and then the tasks will be processed by the VEC server.



%The sets $\mathcal{G} = \left\{mmWave,dsrc,cv2i\right\}$ denote the available offloading communication technologies, $\varphi^{g}_{i}$ is the percentage of the task $i \left(i = 1,2,...N\right)$ transmitted by $g$ category offloading techonology, where $g \in\mathcal{G} $ and $\varphi^{mmWave}_{i} +\varphi^{dsrc}_{i} +\varphi^{cv2i}_{i} =1$. Without loss of generality, the time is divided in to $T$ time slots with the equal duration $\varDelta t$, which are designated by the set $\mathcal{T} =\ \left\{1,2,...T \right\}$. To facilitate modeling, we then enumerate some essenstial and reasonbale assumptions. We take the quasi-static scenario into consideration by default, which the wireless channel state information, and the distances between a vehicle and the BS or RSU remain unchanged in a time slot but differ across various time slots. The VEC server has $N$ task queues, each task queue with a buffer of sufficiently large capacity stores the corresponding type task data. The cloud server processes the tasks stored in the queues of the VEC server, and the tasks transfer from BS to the server without delay since the server is deployed nearby the base station. In this paper, we only consider the time of the uplink transmission. Next we will introduce the queue model and formulate the data arrival model, network model and utility functions based on SNC, respectively. For simplicity, the notations adopted in this paper are listed as TABLE \ref{tab1}.


\vspace{-0.2cm}
\subsection{Data Arrival Model}
%The amount of the tasks that arrive at queue $i$ in time slot $t$ is $A_{i}(t)$ bits, thus the cumulative amount of the tasks that arrive at queue $i$ within time interval  $[s_{1},s_{2})$ ($0 \leq s_{1} < s_{2}$) is defined as a bivariate non-decreasing function, i.e.,
%\begin{}
%A_{i}\left(s_{1},s_{2}\right) =A_{i}\left( s_{2}-s_{1}\right)  =\sum\limits_{t = {s_1}}^{{s_2} - 1} {{A_i}(t)}
%\label{eq1}.
%\end{equation}
%Note that for time interval $[t,t+1)$, there holds
%\begin{equation}
%A_{i}\left(t,t+1\right) =A_{i}(t).
%\label{eq1_2}
%\end{equation}

% According to the SNC theory \cite{ref10}, t
The cumulative amount of the tasks that arrive at queue $i$ within time interval  $[s_{1},s_{2})$ ($0 \leq s_{1} < s_{2}$) is denoted as $ A_{i}\left( s_{1},s_{2}\right) = \sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}} a_{i}(t)$. It has the statistical envelope $\left( \rho_{i} ,\sigma_{i} \right)$ which is referred to as the exponentially bounded burstiness (EBB) and defined to provide a guarantee of the form with a violation probability $\varepsilon^{a}_{i}$\cite{2019guo},
\begin{equation}
P[A_{i}\left( s_{1},s_{2}\right) >\rho_{i} (s_{2}-s_{1}) + \sigma_{i}] \leq \varepsilon^{a}_{i},
\label{eq2}
\end{equation}
where $\rho_{i}$ and $\sigma_{i}$ are the envelope and burstiness of the $i$th type of tasks, respectively. For Poisson task we have $\rho_{i} =\frac{\lambda_i}{\theta} \left(e^{\theta d_i}-1\right) $ and $\sigma_{i} = 0$, here ${\theta} $ is the positive free parameter.

\subsection{Network Service Model}
\label{section_newrork_service}
Next, we will introduce the network service model of mmWave, DSRC and C-V2I. The concept of network service in SNC is the largest transmission capacity that the system can provide for all arrival tasks after excluding interference.

%According to the SNC, the network service is calculated according to the service rate and service time. Next, we will formulate the service rate and service time of the three communication technologies and further formulate the network services of the three communication technologies.


% to formulate the amount of transmitted data under mmWave, DSRC and C-V2I, respectively.W


%based on the transmission characteristics

%in stochastic network caculus based on the transmission characteristics.}

%In the following subsections, the set $\mathcal{G} = \left\{mmw,dsrc,cv2i\right\}$ denotes the available communication technologies in the VEC, i.e., mmWave, DSRC and C-V2I communication technology. $\varphi^{g}_{i}(t)$ is the percentage of the $i$th type task transmitted by communication technology $g$ in time slot $t$, where $g \in\mathcal{G} $ and $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t) +\varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t) +\varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t) =1$.
\subsubsection{Network Service Model of mmWave}

The small-scale fading effects are shown to be negligible in mmWave bands due to the short wavelength and the channel fading is dominated by the shadowing effect\cite{ref31}, thus its transmission rate in time slot $t$ can be calculated according to the Shannon theory, i.e., $C(t)=Blog_{2}\left( 1+\zeta(t)  \gamma_{sinr}(t)  l^{-\delta  }\right)$, where $l$ is the average transmission distance for the vehicles, $\delta$ is the path loss exponent, $\gamma_{sinr}(t)$ is the signal to interference plus noise ratio (SINR) in time slot $t$, $B$ is the aggregated system bandwidth, $\zeta(t)$ is the amplitude of the mmWave channel gain coefficient in time slot $t$. Similar with \cite{ref31} and \cite{ref36}, we consider $\zeta(t)$ follows Nakagami-$m$ distribution, i.e., $\zeta(t)  \sim \Gamma \left( M,M^{-1}\right)$, $M$ is the Nakagami index. Thus the network service of mmWave within a time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$ is given by
\begin{equation}
	\begin{aligned}
	& \beta^{mmw} \left( s_{1},s_{2}\right)  \\& \qquad =\sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}} C(t) =\eta \sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}} In\left( 1+\zeta(t) \gamma_{sinr}(t) l^{-\delta  }\right)
	\end{aligned},
	\label{eq6}
\end{equation}
where $\eta =Blog_{2}e$ and $t\in[s_{1},s_{2})$. Assuming that $\gamma_{sinr}(t)$ and $\zeta(t)$ are independent and identically distributed, we can further get $\beta^{mmw} \left( s_{1},s_{2}\right)  = \eta In\left( 1+\zeta \gamma_{sinr} l^{-\delta  }\right)\left(s_{2}-s_{1}\right)$.

%We assume that the channel gain coefficient is independent and identically distributed for different time slots, i.e., $\zeta(t)$ is a constant within $[s_{1},s_{2})$, and the time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$ is much small, $l(t)$ and $\gamma_{sinr}(t)$ are constant within $[s_{1},s_{2})$. Hence, Eq. \eqref{eq6} can be rewritten as
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
%\beta^{mmw} \left( s_{1},s_{2}\right) = \eta In\left( 1+\zeta(t)  \gamma_{sinr}(t) l(t)^{-\delta  }\right) (s_{2}-s_{1})
%\end{aligned}. 	
%\label{eq7}
%\end{equation}

%The third equivalent in Eq. \eqref{eq7} holds because we assume the channel gain coefficient is i.i.d over the time, i.e, $\zeta^{(q)} \stackrel{\ell}{=} \zeta$.

%According to the Leftover service theorem\cite{ref32}, when mmWave is adopted, the $i$th type of tasks would compete with the other types of tasks for the network service.

According to the notion of leftover service, the network service of mmWave for the $i$th type of tasks is calculated as
%
%Since the interval time $[s_{1},s_{2})$ is small, $\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)$ in time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$ can be deemed as a constant, the network service of mmWave provided for the other types of tasks is $\sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)} A_{j}(s_{1},s_{2})$.
\begin{equation}
	\begin{aligned}
	& \beta _{i,comm}^{mmw} \left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right)  \\ & = \qquad {\left[ {{\beta ^{mmw}}(s_{1},s_{2})
			- \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)} a_{j}(t)
			} \right]^+}
	\end{aligned},
	\label{eq8}
\end{equation}
where $\left[ x\right]^{+}=max\left( x,0\right)$, $\sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)} a_{j}(t)$ is the network service of mmWave for the other types of tasks, which reflects the interference from transmitting the other types of tasks with the same spectrum resources in the communication transmission. Since the network service of mmWave is much larger than the total amount of the tasks, the symbol "$+$" in Eq. \eqref{eq8} can be ignored and we can further get

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
&\beta _{i,comm}^{mmw} \left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = -\sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)}\sigma_j + \\ &\qquad
	 \left[ {\beta ^{mmw}}(s_{1},s_{2}) - \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)}\rho _j\right](s_{2}-s_{1})
%		-\\ & \qquad \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)}\sigma_j 	\\
\end{aligned}.
\label{eq8_2}
\end{equation}

%In the later subsections we will make the same assumptions for DSRC and CV2I.
We use  $\xi _{i,comm}^{mm\omega }(t) = {\beta ^{mmw}}(s_{1},s_{2}) - \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)}\rho _j$ to denote the service envelope, and the burstiness is $\eta _{i,comm}^{mm\omega}(t) = \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{mmw}(t)}\sigma_j$. Thus the network service for the $i$th type tasks transmitted by mmWave can be
%In this case, substituting Eq. \eqref{eq7} into Eq. \eqref{eq8_2}, $\beta _{i,comm}^{mmw}\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right)$ can be written as
\begin{equation}
\beta _{i,comm}^{mmw}\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = \xi _{i,comm}^{mm\omega }(t) (s_{2}-s_{1}) - \eta _{i,comm}^{mm\omega}(t).
\label{eq9}
%\vspace{-0.1cm}
\end{equation}
%where $\xi _{i,comm}^{mm\omega }(t) = \eta In\left( 1+\zeta  \gamma_{sinr} l^{-\delta  }\right)- \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N {\varphi _j^{mm\omega }}(t) {n _i}{\rho _j}$ and $\eta _{i,comm}^{mm\omega } = \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N {\varphi _j^{mm\omega }}(t) {n_{j}}{\sigma _j}$.

\subsubsection{Network Service Model of DSRC}
%DSRC communication based on IEEE 802.11p standard protocol operates at a 5.9 GHz band ranging from 5.850 GHz to 5.925 GHz.
According to the IEEE 802.11p standard, the access delay is the predominant delay of DSRC \cite{ref2}. Therefore, according to the classical latency-rate service\cite{ref33}, the network service of DSRC is calculated as
\begin{equation}
	{\beta ^{dsrc}}\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = {R^{dsrc}}{\left[ {(s_{2}-s_{1}) - {{\hat t}_{serv}}} \right] }{\rm{ }},
	\label{eq10}
%	\vspace{-0.1cm}
\end{equation}
where $R^{dsrc}$ is the largest transmission capacity that the system provide to transmitted by the DSRC, $\hat{t}_{serv}$ is the average access delay of DSRC which has a Pareto-type tail with an exponent of $\partial$ \cite{2016Kat}, i.e., $\hat{t}_{serv} \sim u\left( R^{dsrc}\right)^{-\partial }$, where $u$ is a constant\cite{2015Cho}. Similar to Eqs. \eqref{eq8}-\eqref{eq8_2},  the network service of DSRC for the $i$th type of tasks is modeled as
\begin{equation}
	\begin{aligned}
		& \beta _{i,comm}^{dsrc} \left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = - {R^{dsrc}}{\hat t_{serv}} - \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N {\varphi _j^{dsrc}{n_{j}}} {\sigma _j} + \\ & \qquad
		 \left[ {\beta ^{dsrc}}(s_{1},s_{2}) - \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{dsrc}(t)}\rho _j\right](s_{2}-s_{1})
%			-  \\ & \qquad {R^{dsrc}}{\hat t_{serv}} - \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N {\varphi _j^{dsrc}{n_{j}}} {\sigma _j}		
	\end{aligned}.
	\label{eq11}
\end{equation}
Thus the network service for the $i$th type tasks transmitted by DSRC can be
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccccc}
\beta _{i,comm}^{dsrc}\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = \xi _{i,comm}^{dsrc}(t)(s_{2}-s_{1}) - \eta _{i,comm}^{dsrc}(t)
\end{array},
\label{eq12}
\end{equation}
where $ \xi _{i,comm}^{dsrc}(t) = {\beta ^{dsrc}}(s_{1},s_{2}) - \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N \sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} {\varphi _j^{dsrc}(t)}\rho _j $,  $ \eta _{i,comm}^{dsrc}(t) = {R^{dsrc}}{\hat t_{serv}} + \sum\limits_{j \ne i}^N {\varphi _j^{dsrc}(t){n_{j}}} {\sigma _j}$.

\subsubsection{Network Service Model of C-V2I}
%C-V2I in Release 14 will reserve resources for vehicles, we establish the network service of C-V2I as a bandwidth reservation model.

C-V2I is a communication technology pre-reserved bandwidth resources for vehicles in advance. Once the bandwidth resources are allocated for vehicles to transmit the $i$th type of tasks, the vehicles allocated with different bandwidth resources would not compete the network service with the other types of tasks. Hence, the network service of C-V2I for the $i$th type of tasks is calculated as
\begin{equation}
	{\beta_{i,comm}^{cv2i}}\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = R_i^{cv2i}(s_{2}-s_{1})
	\label{eq13},
\end{equation}
where $R_i^{cv2i}$ is the largest transmission capacity that the system provide to transmitted by C-V2I. For the sake of facilitating derivations, Eq. \eqref{eq13} is unified as the same formation as Eqs. \eqref{eq9} and \eqref{eq12}, i.e.,
\begin{equation}
\beta _{i,comm}^{cv2i}\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = \xi _{i,comm}^{cv2i}(t)(s_{2}-s_{1}) - \eta _{i,comm}^{cv2i}(t)
\label{eq14},
\end{equation}
where $\xi _{i,comm}^{cv2i}(t) = {R_i^{cv2i}}$ and $\eta _{i,comm}^{cv2i}(t) = 0$.

\subsection{Computing Service Model}
%In this subsection, we will model the computing service based on the processing capacity of the VEC server to formulate the amount of the data processed by the VEC server.

%Denote by $\beta _i^{comp}(s_{1},s_{2})$

The computing service for the $i$th type of tasks is the amount of the tasks offloaded by the three communication technologies and processed by the VEC server within time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$, thus the computing service provided for the $i$th type of tasks is calculated as
\begin{equation}
\beta _{i,{comp}}(s_{1},s_{2}) = \sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}} \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i(t)}}}{{{\omega _i}}}.
\label{eq150}
\end{equation}

%Since the interval time $[s_{1},s_{2})$ is relatively small, $\alpha_{i}(t)$ in time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$ can be deemed as a constant, thus we have
%
%\begin{equation}
%\beta _{i,{comp}}(s_{1},s_{2}) = \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i}}} (s_{2}-s_{1})
%\label{eq15}.
%\end{equation}
%that the server is capable of offering to the $i$th type task offloaded to the server at the time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$, equivalent to the amount of tasks processed by the VEC server in Eq. \eqref{eq3}.

%Let $A_i^{g}(s_{1},s_{2})$ be the amount of the $i$th type task transmitted by communication technology $g$ within the time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$, thus it is calculated as
%
%\begin{equation}
%A_{i}^{g}\left( s_{1},s_{2}\right)  =\varphi _i^{g}(t)n_{i}(t) \left[ \rho_{i} \tau  +\sigma_{i} \right],
%\label{eq151}
%\end{equation}

%The computing service provided for the $i$th type task offloaded by communication technology $g$  within the time interval $[s_{1},s_{2})$ is denoted by $\Omega_{i,comp}^g\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right)$.


According to the Leftover service theorem, the $i$th type of tasks offloaded by communication technology $g$ would compete the computing service with those offloaded by the other communication technologies. The amount of the $i$th type of tasks offloaded by other communication technologies and processed by the VEC server within $[s_{1},s_{2})$ is
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{\mathcal{G}/{\rm{g}}}  \sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}}  {A_{i,comp}^{\rm{g}}\left( s_{1},s_{2}\right)} =  \sum_{\mathcal{G}/{\rm{g}}} \sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}}\varphi _i^{g}(t) \left[ \rho_{i} (s_{2}-s_{1})  +\sigma_{i} \right]
\end{aligned},
\label{eq151}
\end{equation}
where ${\mathcal{G}/{\rm{g}}}$ indicates the communication technologies excluding communication technology $g$, thus the computing service of communication technology $g$ provided for the $i$th type of tasks is calculated as
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\beta _{i,comp}^g\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right)  = { \beta _{i,{comp}}(s_{1},s_{2}) - \sum_{\mathcal{G}/{\rm{g}}} \sum^{s_{2}-1}_{t=s_{1}} {A_{i,comp}^{\rm{g}}\left( s_{1},s_{2}\right)}}
\end{aligned}.
\label{eq152}
\end{equation}
\vspace{-1cm}
\subsection{Low Latency Constraint}
Since the task arrival and network service are stationary random process, the probabilistic delay upper bound is adopted to define $\omega _i^g(t)$ to reflect the performance, which is defined as
\begin{equation}
P\left( {W_i^g\left( t \right) \ge \omega _i^g(t)} \right)  \le {\varepsilon_{i}},
\label{eq21_1}
\end{equation}
where ${\varepsilon_{i}}$ is the violation probability, $W_i^g\left( t \right)$ is the delay of the $i$th type of tasks transmitted by communication technology $g$, which is calculated as \cite{2006Filder}
\begin{equation}
W_i^g\left( t \right)= inf\left\{ {w_i \ge 0:\left( {A_i \oslash S_i^g} \right)\left( {t + \omega _i^g(t),t} \right) \le 0} \right\},
\label{eq20}
\end{equation}
where $\oslash$ is the mini-plus deconvolution operator, here $S_i^g(t + \omega _i^g(t),t)$ is the system service of communication technology $g$ for the $i$th type of tasks, which consists of network service and computing service.


%According to concatenation theorem in SNC, the two services constitute a tandem service\cite{ref33}, thus $S_i^g(s ,t+\omega _i^g(t))$ is calculated as
%\begin{equation}
%S_i^g\left( {s ,t + \omega _i^g(t)} \right) = \left( {\beta _{i,comm}^g \otimes \beta _{i,comp}^g} \right)({s ,t + \omega _i^g(t)}),
%\label{eq18}
%\end{equation}
%where $\otimes$ is the mini-plus convolution operator.
%
%According to the mini-plus deconvolution operation and the mini-plus convolution operation rule\cite{2001Le}, we have
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
% & \left( {A_i \oslash S_i^g} \right)\left( t + \omega _i^g(t),t \right) = \\ & \qquad \qquad \qquad  \mathop {\sup }\limits_{0 \le s \le u^{\prime}} \left\{ {A_i\left( {s ,t} \right) - S_i^g\left( {s ,t+\omega _i^g(t)} \right)} \right\}.
%\end{aligned}
%\label{eq21}
%\end{equation}
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
%& \left( {\beta _{i,comm}^g \otimes \beta _{i,comp}^g} \right)\left( {s ,t + \omega _i^g(t)} \right)   = \\ & \qquad \mathop {\inf }\limits_{s \le z \le t+\omega _i^g(t)} \left\{ {\beta _{i,comm}^g\left( {s,z } \right) + \beta _{i,comp}^g\left( {z,t+\omega _i^g(t)} \right)} \right\}.
%\end{aligned}
%\label{eq19}
%\end{equation}

According to Eq. \eqref{eq20} and delay bound theorem \cite{2006Filder}, Eq. \eqref{eq21_1} can be converted to
\begin{equation}
P\left( {W_i^g\left( t \right) \ge \omega _i^g(t)} \right) = P\left( {A_i \oslash S_i^g\left( {t + \omega _i^g(t),t} \right) \ge 0} \right).
\label{eq22}
\end{equation}

The upper bound of $P\left( {W_i^g\left( t \right) \ge \omega _i^g(t)} \right)$ can be obtained as
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
& P\left( {W_i^g\left( t \right) \ge \omega _i^g(t)} \right) \le   \frac{{{e^{\theta \left( {{\sigma _i} + \eta _{i,comm}^{g}(t) + \eta _{i,comp}^{g}(t)} \right)}}}}{{{e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}}} }\\ & \left\{ {\frac{{{e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)\omega _i^g(t)}}}}{{{e^{\theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {e^{\theta \varphi^{g}_{i}(t){\rho _i}}}}} - \frac{{{e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)\omega _i^g(t)}}}}{{{e^{\theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} - {e^{\theta\varphi^{g}_{i}(t){\rho _i}}}}}} \right\}
\end{aligned}.
\label{eq23_12}
\end{equation}
\textit{proof:} See Appendix A.

After setting the upper bound equal to ${\varepsilon_{i}}$, a closed-form solution of $\omega _i^g(t)$ can be obtained, i.e.,
\begin{equation}
\omega _i^g(t) =
\begin{cases}
&\frac{{ - In({\varepsilon_{i}})}}{{\theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} + \frac{\Delta }{{\xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} - {\chi ^{g}}, \\
&\qquad \qquad \qquad {\xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t) > \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)} \\
&\frac{{ - In({\varepsilon_{i}})}}{{\theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} + \frac{\Delta }{{\xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {\chi ^{comp}}, \\
&\qquad \qquad \qquad {\xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t) > \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}
\end{cases}
\label{eq28},
\end{equation}
where $\Delta={\sigma _i} + \eta _{i,comm}^{g}(t) + \eta _{i,comp}^{g}(t)$, $	{\chi ^{g}}={\frac{{In[({e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} - {e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}})({e^{\theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} - {e^{\theta {\varphi^{g}_{i}(t)}{\rho _i}}})]}}{{\theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}}}$ and ${\chi ^{comp}}={\frac{{In[({e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}})({e^{\theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {e^{\theta {\varphi^{g}_{i}(t)}{\rho _i}}})]}}{{\theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}}}$.
%\textit{proof:} See Appendix B.
%\begin{equation}
%	{\chi ^{g}}={\frac{{In[({e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} - {e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}})({e^{\theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}} - {e^{\theta {\varphi^{g}_{i}(t)}{\rho _i}}})]}}{{\theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}}}
%\end{equation}
%\begin{equation}
%{\chi ^{comp}}={\frac{{In[({e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {e^{ - \theta \xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)}})({e^{\theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}} - {e^{\theta {\varphi^{g}_{i}(t)}{\rho _i}}})]}}{{\theta \xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)}}}
%\end{equation}
From Eq. \eqref{eq28}, we can get an important conclusion, i.e., the upper bound $\omega _i^g(t)$ is determined by the less service between the computing service $\xi _{i,{comp}}^g(t)$ and the network service $\xi _{i,{comm}}^g(t)$.

%According to Eq. \eqref{eq28}, given $\varepsilon_{i}$, $\rho_{i}$, $\sigma_{i}$ of the $i$th type of tasks, $\omega _i^g(t)$ can be determined by $\beta _{i,comm}^{g}(t)$, $\beta _{i,comp}^{g}(t)$, $\varphi _i^{g}(t)$ and $\alpha_i(t)$. In addition, according to Eqs. \eqref{eq8_2}, \eqref{eq11} and \eqref{eq150}, $\beta _{i,comm}^{g}(t)$ and $\beta _{i,comp}^{g}(t)$ are determined by  $\varphi _i^{g}(t)$ and $\alpha_i(t)$, thus $\omega _i^g(t)$ depends on $\varphi _i^{g}(t)$ and $\alpha_i(t)$, given $\varepsilon_{i}$, $\rho_{i}$, $\sigma_{i}$. Therefore, once ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t)$ and ${\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)$ for the $i$th task type are calculated, we can determine whether the low latency constraint is satisfied.

The communications in the VEC are low-latency if the delay upper bound satisfies the maximum latency requirement
\begin{equation}
\max \{ \omega _i^{mmw}(t),\omega _i^{dsrc}(t),\omega _i^{cv2i}(t)\}  \le T_i^{\max }, \forall i \in \mathcal{N}, \forall t \in \mathcal{T},
\label{eq17_3}
\end{equation}
where $\omega _i^{mmw}(t)$, $\omega _i^{dsrc}(t)$ and $\omega _i^{cv2i}(t)$ are the delay upper bounds of the $i$th type of tasks transmitted by mmWave, DSRC and C-V2I in time slot $t$, respectively, and  $T_{i}^{max}$ is the maximum latency requirement of the $i$th type of tasks.
\vspace{-0.2cm}
\subsection{Ultra Reliability Constraint}
The required frequencies per bit of data are different for various types of tasks. Let $w_{i}$ be the required frequency to process per bit of the $i$th type of tasks, thus the amount of the $i$th types of tasks processed by the VEC server in time slot $t$ is calculated as $\frac{f_{E} \alpha_{i}(t)}{\omega_{i}}$. Thus the backlog of the $i$th type of tasks in queue $i$ in time slot $t+1$ is calculated as
\begin{equation}
q_{i}(t+1)=\left[q_{i}(t)+a_{i}(t)-\frac{f_{E} \alpha_{i}(t)}{\omega_{i}}\right]^{+},
\label{eq3}
\end{equation}
where $q_{i}(t)$ is the backlog of queue $i$ in time slot $t$.

The reliability of communication is influenced by the stability of the queue. Specifically, if a queue becomes overloaded, the tasks that will arrive at the queue may be dropped, hence the stability of the queue directly impacts the handling of tasks and the reliability of communication. The ultra reliable communications are achieved by maintaining strong stability of each queue $i$ \cite{neely2010stochastic}, i.e.,
\begin{equation}
\mathop {\lim }\limits_{t \to \infty } \sup\frac{1}{t} \sum^{t-1}_{m =0} \sum\limits_{i  = 1}^{N } \mathbb{E}\left[ q_{i}\left( m \right)  \right]  <\infty, \quad \forall i \in \mathcal{N}, \forall t \in \mathcal{T}.
\label{eq17_2}
\end{equation}
\vspace{-1cm}
\subsection{System Utility}
The system utility consists of the communication utility and computation utility.
%due to offloading tasks
%generated by processing the tasks in the VEC server
\subsubsection{Communication Utility}
The communication utility is defined as the charges to offload tasks. As C-V2I works on the licensed band\cite{2020Chen}, while DSRC and mmWave operate on the license-free band \cite{2017Ghasempour,2019Mavromatics}, thus only C-V2I will generate charges for data transmission. In this case, the communication utility to offload the $i$th type of tasks in time slot $t$ is
\begin{equation}
{F_{comm,i}}(t) = {c^{comm}}\sum\limits_{t=s_{1}}^{s_{2}-1} \varphi _i^{cv2i}(t)a_{i}(t)
\label{eq29},
\end{equation}
where $c^{comm}$ is the unit price to offload one Megabyte of tasks through C-V2I.

%Note that the system-level communication costs, i.e., each type of task arriving at the BS is generated by multiple vehicles.
\subsubsection{Computation Utility}
The computation utility is defined as the charges of the power consumption at the VEC server due to task processing. The unit price of power consumption is $c^{comp}$ and the power consumption of each CPU $n_e$ (${n_e} = 1,2,...,N_E$) is $P_{n_e}^{comp}$. Thus, the computation utility of each CPU $n_e$ in time slot $t$ can be expressed as
${F_{comp,n_e}}(t) = {c^{comp}} P_{n_e}^{comp}$. According to the dynamic voltage frequency scaling (DVFS) approach which has been widely applied to construct the realistic CPU power consumption \cite{2014mittal}, $P_{n_e}^{comp}$ is calculated as
\begin{equation}
P_{n_e}^{comp} = \kappa {\left( {{f_E}\sum\limits_{j = 1}^N {{\alpha _j(t)}} /{N_E}} \right)^3}
\label{eq31_0},
\end{equation}
where $\kappa$ is the hardware-related effective switching capacitance parameter.

Based on the above analysis, the system utility is calculated as
\vspace{-0.5cm}
\begin{equation}
F(t) = {\varpi _1}\sum\limits_{{n_e} = 1}^{{N_E}} {{F_{comp,{n_e}}}(t)}  + {\varpi _2}\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{F_{comm,i}}(t)}
\label{eq31},
%\vspace{-0.5cm}
\end{equation}

where ${\varpi _1}$  and ${\varpi _2}$ are the normalized weighting factors to ensure that the magnitudes of the communication utility and computation utility are uniformed.
\vspace{-0.2cm}
\subsection{Optimization Problem}
Our optimization problem aims to minimize the system utility under the resource constraint and the URLLC constraint. Thus the optimal problem is formulated as
\begin{subequations}
\begin{align}
&\label{eq32_a}P1:\qquad \qquad \mathop {\min }\limits_{{\boldsymbol{\alpha }}\left( t \right),{\boldsymbol{\varphi }}\left( t \right)} F(t)\\
s.t.,\;\; &\label{eq32_c} \mathop {\lim }\limits_{t \to \infty } sup\frac{1}{t}\sum\limits_{m  = 0}^{t - 1}  \sum\limits_{i  = 1}^{N } \mathbb{E} \left[ {{q_i}\left( m  \right)} \right] < \infty  \\
& \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad, \forall i \in \mathcal{N}, \forall t \in \mathcal{T} 		
\\ & \label{eq32_b}\max \{ \omega _i^{mmw}(t), \omega _i^{dsrc}(t),\omega _i^{cv2i}(t)\}  \le T_i^{\max } \\
& \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad,\forall i \in \mathcal{N}, \forall t \in \mathcal{T}
\\ &\label{eq32_d} \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{\alpha _i(t)}}  \le 1, \quad \forall i \in \mathcal{N}, \forall t \in \mathcal{T} \\
&\label{eq32_e} \sum\limits_{g \in G} {\varphi _i^g(t)}  = 1, \quad \forall i \in \mathcal{N}, \forall t \in \mathcal{T},
\end{align}
\label{eq32}
\end{subequations}
where ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t) = \left[ {{\alpha _1}(t),{\alpha _2}(t),...,{\alpha _N}(t)} \right]$ is the computation resource allocation policy in time slot $t$.
%i.e., the set of the partition proportion of the CPU frequency allocated to each type of tasks in time slot $t$,
${\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t) = \left[ {\varphi _1^{g}(t),\varphi _2^{g}(t),....\varphi _N^{g}(t)} \right]$ is the communication resource allocation policy,
%i.e., the set of the proportion of the three communication technologies allocated to offload each type of tasks in time slot $t$,
here ${\varphi _i^{g}}(t) = [\varphi _i^{mmw}(t),\varphi _i^{dsrc}(t),\varphi _i^{cv2i}(t)]$.
Constraint \eqref{eq32_b} is the low latency constraint and constraint \eqref{eq32_c} is the ultra reliability constraint; constraint \eqref{eq32_d} guarantees that the CPU frequency allocated to process all types of tasks cannot exceed the total available CPU frequency; and constraint \eqref{eq32_e} imposes all type of tasks to be offloaded.

It is noteworthy that the decision variables in constraints \eqref{eq32_c} and \eqref{eq32_b} are intertwined. Moreover, addressing the long-term constraint \eqref{eq32_c} needs the future insights into the random channel conditions and data arrivals, which are difficult to estimate. Furthermore, the delay upper bound for offloading each type of task through communication technology $g$ is not isolated. The complexity of the above interactions makes it extremely difficult to address the optimization problem $P1$ using the traditional optimization methods. To overcome these challenges, next we propose a Lyapunov-Guided DRL method to convert and solve the optimization problem.

%To overcome these challenges, we propose a Lyapunov-Guided DRL method to solve the optimization problem.
\vspace{-0.3cm}
\section{Lyapunov-Guide DRL Based Conversion and Solution}
%the delay upper bound of offloading tasks in the VEC
%\vspace{-0.2cm}
In this section, we propose a Lyapunov-Guided DRL method to convert and solve the optimization problem. Specifically, since the Lyapunov optimization technique can be employed to deal with these long-term constraints effectively, we first adopt the Lyapunov optimization to converting the long-term constraints into a more tractable form that does not require knowledge of future events. After that, due to that DRL has its ability to learn and optimize policies over time and can dynamically adapt the policies according to the real-time network conditions to maximize the system performance, we then employ DRL for efficient decision-making in the face of complex interactions among different types of tasks and different communication technologies in the heterogeneous VEC.
\vspace{-0.3cm}
%The DRL approach ensures that the solution to $P1$ is both robust and efficient, capable of adapting to the intricate dynamic vehicular networks.

\subsection{Lyapunov-Based Conversion for the Long-Term Constraint}

%In this sub-section, we will transform the ultra reliability constraint into an short-term decision problem based on the Lyapunov optimization, which is  an efficient framework without requiring any future information.

In this section, we apply the Lyapunov optimization to convert $P1$ into short-term decision problem. Let $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ be the conditional Lyapunov drift in time slot $t$ which is calculated as \cite{neely2010stochastic}
\begin{equation}
\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right) \buildrel \Delta \over = \mathbb{E}\left\{ {L\left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t+1) \right) - L\left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)|\boldsymbol{Q}(t)} \right\}
\label{eq34},
\end{equation}
where $\boldsymbol{Q}(t) = \left[ q_1(t),q_2(t),...q_N(t)\right]$ is the queue backlog, $L\left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ is the Lyapunov function which measures the average queue backlog in time slot $t$, and is calculated as $L\left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right) = \frac{1}{2}\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{q_i}} {\left( t \right)^2}$. Based on the property that $\left\{ [x]^{+} \right\}^{2} = {(\max [x,0])^2} \le {x^2} $ ($x \in \mathbb{R}$), $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ is upper bounded by
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
& \Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right) \le
\frac{1}{2} \mathbb{E}  \left\{
	\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N
	{
	{{ \left({{a_i}(t)^2 + \left[\frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}\right]^2}\right)}}\left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.
	}  \right\}
	+ \\
	& \quad
\frac{1}{2} \mathbb{E}  \left\{
	\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N
	{{q_i}(t)
	\left({a_i}(t) - \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \right)
	\left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.
	}
\right\}
\\
&
\le B + \frac{1}{2} \mathbb{E}  \left\{
	\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N
	{{q_i}(t)
	\left({a_i}(t) - \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \right)
	\left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.
	}
\right\}
%\le B + {\mathbb{E}\left\{ \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{{q_i}(t){a_i}(t) \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}} - \\ &  \qquad {\mathbb{E}\left\{ \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq34_3},
\end{equation} where B is a constant obtained as
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
 & \mathbb{E} \left\{ \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{{ \left({{a_i}(t)^2 + \left[\frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}\right]^2}\right)}}} | {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right\}   \\
&  \qquad  \le \sum \limits_{i = 1}^N \mathbb{E}\left\{{a_i}(t)^2| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right\} +  \sum \limits_{i = 1}^N \mathbb{E} \left\{\left[\frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}\right]^2 | {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right\} \\
& \qquad  \le  \sum \limits_{i = 1}^N \left(a_{i}\right)^2  +  \sum \limits_{i = 1}^N \left[\frac{{{f_E}}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}\right]^2 = B
\end{aligned}
\label{eq34_4}.
\end{equation} We will apply the opportunistic expectation minimization technique to process  the last two term in Eq. \eqref{eq34_3}. Thus $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ can be upper bound by
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)  & \le B - \left(\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}   -  \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)a_{i}(t) \right)  \\
& = B - \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {q_i}(t) \left( \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}   - a_{i}(t) \right)
\end{aligned}
\label{eq34_5}.
\end{equation}
% =\lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})
%The backlog in queue $i$ is affected by the task arrival in the previous time slot $t-1$, thus ${q_i}(t)$ is a constant in time slot $t$. The second term of the RHS in Eq. \eqref{eq34_3} can be written as
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
% {\mathbb{E}\left\{ \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{{q_i}(t){A_i}(t) \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}} = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t){\mathbb{E}\left\{{{A_i}(t) \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}}
%\end{aligned}
%\label{eq34_33}.
%\end{equation}
%
%Since the task arrival is independent of the queue backlog, we have ${\mathbb{E}\left\{ {{A_i}(t) \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}} ={\mathbb{E}\left\{{A_i}(t)\right\}}$. According to Eq. \eqref{eq2}, we have ${\mathbb{E}\left\{{A_i}(t)\right\}} = \mathbb{E}\left\{ n_{i} \left[ \rho_{i}+\sigma_{i} \right]\right\}= \left[ \rho_{i}+\sigma_{i} \right] \mathbb{E}\left\{ n_{i}\right\}$. Since $n_{i}$ follows a Poisson distribution with arrival rate $\lambda_{i}$ and $\mathbb{E}\left\{ n_{i}\right\}=\lambda_{i}$, Eq. \eqref{eq34_33} can be written as
%% =\lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
%\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t){\mathbb{E}\left\{{{A_i}(t) \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}} = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)[\lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})]
%\end{aligned}
%\label{eq34_32}.
%\end{equation}
%	
%%According the Lyapunov optimization theory\cite{neely2010stochastic}, ???$\frac{1}{2} \mathbb{E} \left\{ \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{[{{  \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}}}]^2}} | {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right\}$ has an upper bound, denoted as $B$, thus we have
%According to the Lyapunov optimization theory\cite{neely2010stochastic}, the third term in Eq. \eqref{eq34_3} has an upper bound, denoted as $B$, thus we have
%
%
%
%Substituting Eqs. \eqref{eq34_32} and \eqref{eq34_4} into \eqref{eq34_3}, we have
%Eq. \eqref{eq34_5} indicates that the conditional Lyapunov drift $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ has an upper bound. The last term can be reorganized as
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
%%\epsilon \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N \mathbb{E}\left\{ \left| q_{i}(t)\right| \right\} =  \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {\mathbb{E}\left\{ {{q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}}
%& \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {\mathbb{E}\left\{ {{q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}}  - \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)[\lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})]  \\ & \quad  = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {q_i}(t) {\mathbb{E}\left\{ {\frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}} - \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)[\lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})]\\ & \quad = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {q_i}(t) \left[{\mathbb{E}\left\{ {\frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}} \left| {\boldsymbol{Q}\left( t \right)} \right.} \right\}} - \lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})\right]
%\end{aligned}
%\label{eq34_51}.
%\end{equation}

Letting $\epsilon$ be $\left( \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}   - a_{i}(t) \right)$, and thus Eq. \eqref{eq34_5} can be rewritten as $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right) \le B-\epsilon\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N  q_{i}(t)$. According to the conditional Lyapunov drift theorem\cite{neely2010stochastic}, if conditional Lyapunov drift $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ is upper bounded by $B-\epsilon\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N  q_{i}(t)$ for each time slot $t \in \mathcal{T} $, we have
%$B-\epsilon\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N \mathbb{E}\left\{ \left| q_{i}(t)\right| \right\}$
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathop {\lim }\limits_{t \to \infty } sup\frac{1}{t}\sum\limits_{m  = 0}^{t - 1}  \sum\limits_{i  = 1}^{N } \mathbb{E} \left[ {{q_i}\left( m  \right)} \right] \le \frac{B}{\epsilon}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq34_6}.
\end{equation}
In this case, the ultra reliability constraint \eqref{eq32_c} can be achieved. Hence, in order to satisfy the constraint \eqref{eq32_c}, we just need to ensure that the conditional Lyapunov drift $\Delta \left( \boldsymbol{Q}(t) \right)$ has a minimum tight upper bound. The optimization objective to guarantee the ultra reliability constraint is to obtain the optimal ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t)$,  given by
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathop {\min }\limits_{{\boldsymbol{\alpha }}\left( t \right)}: \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)a_{i}(t) - \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N { {{q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}}}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq34_7}.
\end{equation}
In Eq. \eqref{eq34_7}, ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t)$ is to determine the queue stability which is obtained based on the current queue backlog $\boldsymbol{Q}(t)$, hence the long-term time-average constraint \eqref{eq32_c} can be transformed to a tractable short-term decision problem.

%\subsection{Optimization Problem Reformulation }

As the objective of $P$1 is to minimize the system utility, we can combine the objective of $P$1 with the short-term optimization objective, i.e., Eq. \eqref{eq34_7}, Thus the optimization problem $P$1 can be converted into the optimization problem $P$2 as follows
\begin{subequations}
\begin{align}
\mathop {\min } \limits_{{\boldsymbol{\alpha }}\left( t \right),{\boldsymbol{\varphi }}\left( t \right)}&:
V \cdot \left(  \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)a_{i}(t)  - \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N { {{q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}} }\right) + F(t) \\
s.t.,& \ \ \eqref{eq32_b}-\eqref{eq32_e},
\end{align}
\vspace{-0.5cm}
\label{eq36}

\end{subequations}
where $V$ is a non-negative coefficient that enables a tradeoff between ultra-reliability and system utility.

However, problem $P$2 is non-convex and the dimensionality is high for the complex and dynamic heterogeneous VEC environment, thus solving problem $P$2 based on the traditional optimization method such as the convex optimization method would cause the curse of dimensionality. Moreover, the traditional optimization method struggle to adapt to dynamic environments and can not provide the real-time solutions, which is critical requirement for high-speed VEC. Consequently, finding a solution for problem $P$2 is far from trivial. In recent years, there has been a growing trend in the research community to employ DRL to solve the non-convex optimization problems. This is due to its robustness and adaptability in solving complex, non-convex problems in dynamic and high-dimensional environments. Therefore, DRL emerges as an ideal choice for addressing problem $P$2 in our study.

%presents substantial challenges due to the curse of dimensionality, a phenomenon made worse by the complex heterogeneous VEC environment. Consequently, finding a solution for problem $P$2 is far from trivial.
%To address this, we employ DRL, a method increasingly being adopted in research to tackle complex optimization problems. DRL is particularly well-suited for handling such problems due to several reasons. Firstly, vehicular environments often present large and complex problem dimensions, and DRL is adopted at managing high-dimensional state and action spaces. Secondly, traditional convex optimization methods may not provide real-time solutions, a requirement crucial in high-speed vehicular environments. In contrast, DRL can offer near real-time solutions by observing the current state of the environment and learning from it.
%Thirdly, the traditional convex optimization methods may struggle to adapt to dynamic environments, whereas DRL can effectively handle dynamic changes due to its ability to learn from interactions with the environment. Furthermore, DRL can learn optimal policies from raw sensory inputs, making it a more flexible and general approach compared to traditional methods.
%In recent years, there has been a growing trend in the research community to employ DRL to solve non-convex optimization problems. This is due to its robustness and adaptability in solving complex, non-convex problems in dynamic and high-dimensional environments. Therefore, DRL emerges as an ideal choice for addressing problem $P$2 in our study.}


\vspace{-0.3cm}
\subsection{Reinforcement Learning-Based Solution}
\subsubsection{DRL Framework Construction}
To address problem $P$2, we model the offloading process as a DRL process, where the VEC server acts as a agent. In each time slot $t$, the VEC server first observes the current state $s_t$, then decides the current action $a_t$ and executes it. After that the VEC server receives a reward $r_t$ from the system, which guides the VEC server in making its next action decision, then the current state $s_t$ is transited to the next state $s_{t+1}$ and the process enters the next time slot. Next, we construct the DRL framework, namely state, action, and reward.

%Once the framework is established, we employ the Soft Actor-Critic (SAC) algorithm to find the optimal policy. The emphasis of this approach is on the role of the VEC server as a reinforcement learning agent in vehicular scenarios, with the ultimate objective of addressing the optimization problem $P$2.

%Next, we construct DRL framework which inlcudes state, action and reward to reflect $P$2. Specially, the VEC server observes the current state $s_t$ and then makes the action $a_t$ based on the state $s_t$ according to policy $\pi_t$, then the  VEC server will enter the next state $s_{t+1}$  and get a reward $r_t$ from environment. The states and actions that the VEC server will constitute a state-action behavioral trajectory $\tau  = ({s_0},{a_0},{s_1},{a_2}, \cdots )$. Then we will adopt the DRL algorithm to solve the DRL framework to obtain the optimal offloading policy.
%\vspace{-0.5cm}
%\subsubsection{State}
\paragraph{State}
 Considering that in vehicular environments the task arrival is random and can be significantly influenced by the mobility and density of vehicles, it is imperative to incorporate this aspect into the state. Therefore, we include the number of tasks that arrive in each time slot $t$, denoted as ${{\cal A}_t} = [{a_1(t)},{a_2(t)},...{a_N(t)}]$, as the first element of the state. Furthermore, the backlog of the queue is another critical factor that influences the ultra-reliability of the system, particularly in the scenarios with high vehicular density\cite{2020Sohee}. Therefore, we consider ${\cal Q}_t = \left[ {{q_1}\left( t \right),{q_2}\left( t \right) ,...{q_N}\left( t \right)} \right]$ as the second element of the state. Moreover, according to Eq. \eqref{eq28}, $\beta _{i,comm}^{g}(t)$ and $\beta _{i,comp}^{g}(t)$ will determine the delay upper bound $\omega _i^g(t)$, and ${\bf{\xi }}_{i,comm}^{g}(t)$ and ${\bf{\xi }}_{i,comp}^{g}(t)$. Since there is no competition among different types of tasks in C-V2I and mmWave has sufficient radio resources, $\beta _i^{cv2i}(t)$ and $\beta _i^{mmw}(t)$ are independent of time slot $t$. \hl{${\bf{\xi}}_{i,comm}^{g}(t)$ and ${\bf{\xi }}_{i,comp}^{g}(t)$  which represent the remaining resources determine $\beta _{i,comm}^{g}(t)$ and $\beta _{i,comp}^{g}(t)$}, hence we consider  ${{\boldsymbol{\xi }}_t} = \left[ {{{\boldsymbol{\xi }}_1}(t),{{\boldsymbol{\xi }}_2}(t),...{{\boldsymbol{\xi }}_N}(t)} \right]$ as the third element of the state, where ${{\boldsymbol{\xi }}_i}(t) = \left[ {{\bf{\xi }}_{i,comm}^{dsrc}(t),{\bf{\xi }}_{i,comp}^{cv2i}(t),{\bf{\xi }}_{i,comp}^{mmw}(t),{\bf{\xi }}_{i,comp}^{dsrc}(t)} \right]$. Therefore, the state of the reinforcement learning framework, as observed by the VEC server at time slot $t$, is formulated as
\begin{equation}
{s_t} = \left[ {{{\cal A}_t},{{\cal Q}_t},{{\boldsymbol{\xi }}_t}} \right]
\label{eq37}.
\end{equation}
%the dimension of ${s}_t$???


%This state representation allows the VEC server to observe the crucial elements that affect the system's performance in vehicular scenarios and make decisions that optimize the desired metrics.
%The random task arrival affects the stability, latency and system utility. Hence, we consider the amount of arrived tasks in each slot $t$, i.e., ${{\cal A}_t} = [{a_1(t)},{a_2(t)},...{a_N(t)}]$, as the first element of the state. In addition, the queue backlog affects the ultra reliability performance\cite{2020Sohee}, and thus we consider ${\cal Q}_t = \left[ {{q_1}\left( t \right),{q_2}\left( t \right) ,...{q_N}\left( t \right)} \right]$ as the second element of the state. Considering the channel characteristics of mmWave and assuming that the BS knows the time-varying channel gain, we include the channel gain $\zeta(t)$ as an state as well. Here, we use $\zeta_t$ to express $\zeta(t)$. Therefore, the state of the DRL framework in time slot $t$ is designed as
%\begin{equation}
%{s_t} = \left[ {{{\cal A}_t},{{\cal Q}_t},\zeta_t} \right]
%\label{eq37}.
%\end{equation}

%\vspace{-1.5cm}
%\subsubsection{Action}
\paragraph{Action}
%The system adjusts ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t) $ and ${\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)$ in each time slot $t$, and thus the action of the DRL framework in time slot $t$ is formulated as ${a}_t = \left[ {{\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t),{\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)} \right]$.
%\begin{equation}
%{a}_t = \left[ {{\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t),{\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)} \right]
%\label{eq38}.
%\end{equation}
The VEC server takes actions to adjust ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t) $ and ${\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)$ in each time slot $t$, thus the action taken by the VEC server in time slot $t$ in the DRL framework is given by
\begin{equation}
{a}_t = \left[ {{\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t),{\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)} \right]
\label{eq38}.
\end{equation}
%Note that the dimensions of ${\boldsymbol{\alpha }}(t)$ and ${\boldsymbol{\varphi }}(t)$ are $N$ and $3N$, respectively. Thus, the dimension of ${a}_t$ is $4N$, which is high when the number of task types $N$ is large.

%\subsubsection{Reward Function}
\paragraph{Reward Function}
%In addition, it introduces the policy entropy into the reward, thus  the VEC server can be encouraged to explore more feasible policies while maximizing the reward.

%which introduces policy entropy into the reward, maximizing the reward while encouraging the VEC server to explore more feasible policies. Therefore, SAC has better robustness, stronger generalization ability.}

The target of the DRL is to maximize the long-term discount reward, while we aim to minimize the objective of $P2$, thus the reward of the DRL framework is formulated as the negative of the objective of problem $P2$. In addition, we put a large penalty term into the reward for the penalty that violates the constraint \eqref{eq32_b}. Hence, the reward function is defined as
%\begin{equation}
%\begin{aligned}
%{r_t} =  -\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)[\lambda_{i}(\rho_{i}+\sigma_{i})] + \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N { {{q_i}(t) \frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}} } - V \cdot{F(t)}
%\label{eq39_1}.
%\end{aligned}
%\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
{r_t} & = V \cdot \left(
-\sum\limits_{i = 1}^N{q_i}(t)a_{i}(t) + \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N { {{q_i}(t)\frac{{{f_E}{\alpha _i}(t)}}{{{\omega _i^g(t)}}}} } \right)
- F(t) \\& - P_{e} \cdot \{\max \{ \omega _i^{mmw}(t), \omega _i^{dsrc}(t),\omega _i^{cv2i}(t)\} - T_i^{\max }\}
\label{eq40},
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where $P_{e}$ is a penalty weight.
%$r_t(a_t,s_t)$ accounts for the reward feedback from the environment to the VEC server after taking action $a_t$ on the state $s_t$.

%The state and action of the DRL framework are high-dimensional continuous variables, the SAC algorithm adopts the neural networks to approximate the high-dimensional state and action, and adopts the policy gradient to solve problem with continuous state and action.


