%in order to compare the performance of delay upper bound among different communications, we set the  transmission rate same as DSRC, i.e., each type tasks will obtain the transmission rate $R_{i}^{cv2i}=27$ Mbps through C-V2I. In particular, the mmWave communication configurations adpot the parameters in \cite{ref36}, the bandwidth is allocated with $B = 20$ MHz, the path loss exponent $\delta = 2.45$, Nakagami-$m$ index $ M = 5$, and the average distance $ l = 1$ km.

%We will evaluate the delay upper bound of offloading tasks through single communication technology, thus there are no other competitive tasks transmitted by other communication technologies, i.e., $\Omega _i^g\left( {s_{1},s_{2}} \right) = \beta _{comp}^{i}(s_{1},s_{2})$ in Eq. \eqref{eq16}. In addition, the CPU frequency will be equally allocated to each type of tasks, i.e., $\alpha_i(t)=f_E/N$ in each time slot $t$. We assume $\rho_i$ and $\sigma_i$ are the same for each task type $i$ and $w_i= 10435$, thus the delay upper bounds are the same for each task type $i$. Hence, we only need to observe and analyze the delay upper bound of the first type of tasks. In Figs. \ref{fig_5}-\ref{fig_7}, the violation probability ${\varepsilon_{1}}$   is set to $0.01$. In Figs. \ref{fig_5}-\ref{fig_8}, the simulation results  are obtained through averaging the results of 100 experiments. The experiment includes $50$ time slots, in each of which we assume $n_i = 1$ within time interval $[t,t+1)$. The delay in the last time slot is considered as the delay upper bound.
