%Fig. \ref{fig_5} shows the relationship between the delay upper bound and  task arrival rate $\rho_{1}$ under different number of task types $N$ with single communication technology ($\sigma_{1}=0$ Mbps and $f_{E} = 1500$ GHz). We can see that the delay upper bound increases with $\rho_{1}$ and $N$. This is because as $\rho_{1}$ and $N$ increase, there are more tasks that need to be transmitted and processed. Particularly, the delay upper bound under mmWave and C-V2I increases slowly at first, but when $\rho_{1}$ becomes large, the delay upper bound increases rapidly.
%This is because that the mmWave provides more network service for the first type of tasks than the computing service in the beginning. According to the conclusion obtained by Eq. \eqref{eq28}, the delay upper bound is determined by the less service between computing service and network service, thus the delay upper bound of mmWave is determined by the computing service. Since there is no competition for computing service under single communication technology, the computing service decreases slowly, thus the delay upper bound of mmWave increases slowly at first. As $\rho_{1}$ keeps increasing, the computing service of mmWave is more than the network service, thus the delay upper bound is determined by the network service. Since there are other types of tasks competing the network service of mmWave with the first type of tasks, the network service of mmWave decreases quickly, thus the delay upper bound of mmWave increases rapidly.
%For C-V2I, there is no competition for network service and computing service. According to Eq.  \eqref{eq28}, the delay upper bound of C-V2I is affected by $e^{\theta {\rho _i}}$, thus the trend of the delay upper bound of C-V2I is same as the trend of $e^{\theta {\rho _i}}$ when $\rho_{1}$ increases. However, it is seen that the delay upper bound under DSRC always increases sharply as $\rho_{1}$ increases. This is because that the network service of DSRC is less than its computing service, thus the delay upper of DSRC bound is determined by the network service. Since the first type of tasks need to compete the network service of DSRC with the other types of tasks, the network service of DSRC decreases rapidly as $\rho_{1}$ increases, which results in the delay upper bound under DSRC increases sharply. In addition, we can see that DSRC has the worse performance than mmWave and C-V2I. It's because that the network service of DSRC is less than that of mmWave and C-V2I due to that DSRC is affected by the access delay. Moreover, it is seen that the delay upper bound under mmWave outperforms the two other communication technologies when $\rho_{1}$ is small. It is because at first the delay upper bound of mmWave is determined by the computing service while the delay upper bound of C-V2I and DSRC is determined by the network service, and the computing service of mmWave is more than the network service of C-V2I and DSRC. One key point to be mentioned is that when $\rho_{1}$ becomes large, the delay upper bound under mmWave will exceed that under C-V2I. It is because that as $\rho_{1}$ keeps increasing, the delay upper bound of mmWave is determined by the network service, while the first type of tasks transmitted through mmWave will compete the network service with the other types of tasks, thus as $\rho_{1}$ keeps increasing, the network service is decreased and there will exist the case that the network service of mmWave for the first type of tasks is less than that of C-V2I.
