%Fig. \ref{fig_6} shows the relationship between the delay upper bound and  task burstiness $\sigma_{1}$ under different $N$ and single communication technologies when $\rho_{1}=0.1$ Mbps and $f_{E} = 1500$ GHz. One can see that the delay upper bound has a line relationship with $\sigma_{1}$, which is consistent with Eq. \eqref{eq28}. In addition, it can be seen that as $\sigma_{1}$ increases, the delay upper bound first increases slowly, but when $\sigma_{1}$ becomes large, the slope of the linear becomes large. This is because when $\sigma_{1}$ is small, the VEC server is able to process the offloaded tasks in time. When $\sigma_{1}$ increases, the VEC server cannot process tasks in time and thus the backlog of the queues starts to increase. These backlogged tasks will compete for the CPU frequency with the offloading tasks.
