%Fig. \ref{fig_7} depicts the relationship between the delay upper bound and arrival rate $\rho_{i}$ under different CPU frequency $f_E$ and single communication technologies ($\rho_{1} = 0.1$ Mbps, $\sigma_{1} = 0 $ Mbps, $R^{dsrc}=R^{cv2i}_i =200$ Mbps and $ N = 5$). It is seen that the delay upper bound is smaller under higher CPU frequency. This is because when the CPU frequency is high, the VEC server can allocate more CPU frequency to process tasks in the queues. It is seen that the delay upper bound of all the communication technologies under different CPU frequency increase as $\rho_1$ increases, this is because that the computing service or network service which determines the delay upper bound decreases as $\rho_1$ increases. It is note that the delay upper bound begins to decrease when $\rho_{1}$ increases to 1.1 Mbps for DSRC and 2.2 Mbps for mmWave when $f_{E}=2000$ GHz. It is because that the delay upper bound is also affected by the difference between the network service and computing service for the first type of tasks, where the delay upper bound has the large value when the difference is small. When $\rho_1 = 1.1$ Mbps and $\rho_1 = 2.2$ Mbps, the difference is the small thus there is a large delay upper bound. As $\rho_1$ increases, the difference becomes large, thus the delay upper bound will decreases.


