%Fig. \ref{fig_8} shows the relationship between the violation probability and delay upper bound under various communication resource allocation policies ($\rho_{1} = 0.1$ Mbps, $\sigma_{1} = 0 $ Mbps, $N = 5$ and $f_{E} = 1500$ GHz). The red, blue and green curves represent the relationship under single communication technology mmWave, C-V2I and DSRC, i.e., $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t) = 1$, $\varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t) = 1$ and $\varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t) = 1$, respectively. The purple curves indicate that tasks are offloaded equally by the three communication technologies, i.e., $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t) = \varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t) = \varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t) = \frac{1}{3}$. We can see that when the violation probabilities are the same, the delay upper bound under DSRC is higher than that under mmWave and C-V2I. This is because that DSRC provides less network service than mmWave and does not reserve resource blocks for tasks like C-V2I to avoid tasks competition for network service. Thus, single mmWave and C-V2I have smaller delay upper bound to guarantee a better network performance than single DSRC. It also can be seen that delay upper bounds under single mmWave and C-V2I are smaller than that under heterogeneous communication technologies when the violation probabilities are the same. This is because the delay upper bound of single mmWave is only affected by the competition for network service among tasks. When tasks are transmitted by heterogeneous communications, the delay upper bound of mmWave will be influenced by the competition for computing service under DSRC and C-V2I. Tasks transmitted by C-V2I only compete for computing service, resulting in single C-V2I has smaller delay upper bound. Moreover, we can see that the delay upper bound under single DSRC is larger than that under heterogeneous communication technologies when violation probabilities are the same. This is because that DSRC has less network service. When tasks are transmitted by the heterogeneous communications, there will be less competition for network service among tasks through DSRC since mmWave and C-V2I share their resources to transmit tasks.

