\subsubsection{Training Stage}
Fig. \ref{fig_9} shows the learning curve of the training process under different $V$, where the $y$-axis illustrates the average rewards. The dashed line is the actual reward curve while the solid line is the smooth curve after averaging the actual reward curve. We can see that the learning curve first increases, then decreases, and finally increases slowly to a stable value. This is because that the VEC server will first learn the policy to maximize the reward and guarantee constraint \eqref{eq32_a}, thus learning curve first increases. In the learning process, the constraint \eqref{eq32_a} may be violated and incur a large penalty, hence the learning curve will degrade. Afterwards, the VEC will eventually learns an optimal policy to maximize the reward while satisfying constraints \eqref{eq32_a}, therefore the learning curve will finally become stable. We can also see that the rewards have some jitters after reaching stable, because the VEC server stays in a stochastic environment due to the random task arrival, which will affect the learning of the VEC server.

