\subsubsection{Testing Stage}
%The VEC server will employ the optimal policy to test performance.
We will validate the performance of our policy, which is referred to as LySAC, by comparing the performance of four other baseline policies, i.e.,

\begin{itemize}
%	\item{Random allocation and random offloading (RARO): The total CPU frequency  $f_{E}$ is allocated randomly to each type of tasks (i.e., $\alpha_i(t)$ is random, under the condition $\sum\nolimits_{i = 1}^N  {\alpha _i(t)}\le 1$ ), while each communication technology also transmits a random percentage of tasks, i.e., $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t)$, $\varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t)$ and $\varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t)$ are random.}
	\item{Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO)\cite{2021Keshari}: PSO is an optimization algorithm inspired by the foraging behavior of birds, which has been widely applied in the research on task offloading policies and resource allocation.}
	\item{Heuristic Gibbs Random Algorithm (HGRA)\cite{2021Zhou}: HGRA iteratively determines offloading policy and resource allocation based on the Gibbs distribution, which is composed of a uniform distribution $\rho_g$ and an empirical performance-related distribution $\omega_g$. The distribution $\omega_G$ is updated based on the value from the optimization problem $P2$.}
	\item{Heuristic Gibbs Greedy Algorithm (HGGA): HGGA is a variation of HGRA Algorithm that greedily selects the communication technology with the highest probability as the offloading policy.
\item{Equal allocation and equal offloading (EAEO): The total CPU frequency  $f_{E}$ is equally allocated to $N$ task types, and each communication technology offloads equivalent percentage of tasks, i.e., $\varphi^{mmw}_{i}(t)=\varphi^{dsrc}_{i}(t)=\varphi^{cv2i}_{i}(t) =\frac{1}{3}$ and $\alpha_i(t) = \frac{1}{3} f_{E}$, hence EAEO is independent with $V$.}
}
\end{itemize}

Figs. (\ref{fig_ave_energy}) - (\ref{fig_ave_utility}) present the average computation utility, communication utility, and system utility under different policies and values of $V$. These results are obtained by taking the average across all time steps. From Figs. (\ref{fig_ave_energy}) - (\ref{fig_ave_utility}), we can see that the LySAC utilizes the lower computation utility, this is because that LySAC is capable of intelligently and dynamically adjusting the usage of resources based on a intelligent understanding of the task characteristics, queue backlog, and utility, all while meeting the requirements of URLLC and minimizing the utility. From Fig. \ref{fig_ave_energy}, it can be observed that EAEO utilizes the highest computation utility. This is because EAEO employs all CPU frequencies to process tasks. Moreover, we can see that HGGA, HGRA, and PSO also use more computation utility than the LySAC. This is due to the fact that they do not take into account task characteristics and queue backlog when allocating resources, thus using more CPU frequencies than LySAC to ensure URLLC performance. From Fig. \ref{fig_ave_charge}, it can be seen that EAEO, HGGA, HGRA and PSO use roughly the same amount of communication utility. This is because these four policies do not consider the differences in task characteristics to select communication technology for offloading, thus causing the same charges. Fig. \ref{fig_ave_utility} depicts the system utility, which includes both computation utility and communication utility. Based on the usage of computation utility and communication utility, the system utility of LySAC is significantly lower than that of the other four policies.

On the other hand, in Figs. (\ref{fig_ave_energy}) - (\ref{fig_ave_utility}), HGGA, HGRA and PSO do not exhibit significant changes in the usage of average computation utility, communication utility, and system utility as $V$ changes. This is because these three policies are based on minimizing the objective values and do not take into account the variations in $V$. Meanwhile, the three utilities of EAEO are independent of $V$, so they do not change with $V$. This demonstrates that EAEO, HGGA, HGRA, and PSO fail to adapt to actual requirements. In Fig. \ref{fig_ave_energy}, the average computation utility used by LySAC increases as $V$ increases. This is because as $V$ increases, LySAC places more emphasis on the stability of the queue and thus allocates more CPU frequency. However, when $V=0$, the average computation utility is at its maximum because the LySAC policy pays more attention to meet the latency requirements of the tasks at this point, which typically requires more CPU frequencies. In Fig. \ref{fig_ave_charge}, the trend of communication utility of LySAC with respect to changes in $V$ is exactly opposite to that in \ref{fig_ave_energy}. This is because as LySAC allocates more computational resources to maintain queue stability, it reduces the dependence on communication resources. In Fig. \ref{fig_ave_utility}, the system utility decreases as $V$ increases. This is because the system utility includes the computation and communication utility, and the communication utility constitutes a large proportion of the system utility.
%Fig. (\ref{fig_ave_energy}) - (\ref{fig_ave_utility}) \hl{present the average computation utility, communication utility, and utility of the system under different policies and values of $V$. These results are obtained by taking the average across all time steps.}
%
%
%%The trends observed in the LySAC policy's average energy, communication charge, and utility with respect to changing $V$ suggest that communication charge plays a more significant role in the overall utility.
%Fig. \ref{fig_ave_energy} \hl{reveals that the LySAC policy generates lower ???? than other policies, which means it utilizes the lowest CPU frequencies. EAEO policy employs the highest CPU frequencies, while HGGA, HGRA, and PSO policies use the similar CPU frequencies. LySAC policy also generates lower communication ??? than other policies. Overall, the LySAC policy outperforms other policies in terms of resource utilization efficiency.}
%%The parameter $V$ serves as a tradeoff between queue stability and utility.
%\hl{In Fig.} \ref{fig_ave_charge}, \hl{LySAC policy allocates higher CPU frequencies mainly to meet latency requirements when $V=0$. As $V$ increases, the policy increasingly focuses on the stability of the queue, resulting in increased resource allocation. Moreover, as $V$ increases, the utilization of mmWave and DSRC for task offloading also rises, leading to reduced communication charges due to improved availability of computational resources.
%The average energy, communication charge, and utility of the other policies show little variation with respect to $V$. This suggests they fail to adapt to actual requirements (i.e., the magnitude of $V$, representing stability versus CPU frequency resources), highlighting the LySAC policy's ability to make appropriate decisions based on demands.}
