%Figs. \ref{fig_10a}-\ref{fig_10c} shows the relationship between the violation probability and the delay upper bound of the three types of tasks under different policies, where the corresponding violation probability is calculated as the percentage of the delay which is larger than the delay upper bound. We can see that when ${\varepsilon_{i}} = 0.01$, the optimal policy under various values of $V$ can guarantee that the delay upper bound of each type of tasks is less than $T_{i}^{max}=30$ ms, which validates the effectiveness of the proposed optimal policy. RARO and EAEO policies cannot satisfy the low latency constraint, as they do not take advantage of the three communication technologies. The EAEO has a lower delay upper bound than RARO. The reason is that EAEO will offload more tasks through C-V2I than the proposed optimal policy, resulting in more charges.
%
%Figs. \ref{V_0_len}-\ref{V_100_len} depict the queue backlog of the optimal policy for the 3D game tasks, VR tasks and AR tasks under different $V$. It can be seen that the queue backlog of the optimal policy for the 3D game tasks increases during a period of time and then reach the stability. This is because that the VEC server needs to take some time to learn from the environment and then generate an effective policy. We also can see that the queue backlog of the 3D game tasks is always larger than the two other types of tasks and the queue backlog of the VR and AR tasks always keep stable under different $V$. This is because the required $\omega$ for VR and AR tasks are smaller than that for 3D game tasks, and the percentage of the CPU frequency allocated for VR and AR tasks under the condition of satisfying the low latency can process most of the tasks. In addition, when $V$ is large, the fluctuation of the queue after stabilization also becomes significant. This is because that when $V$ is large, the VEC server will focus on minimizing the system utility, thus the stability of the queue cannot be guaranteed well. Since the queue backlog of the VR and AR tasks always keep stable, next we will focus on the 3D game tasks and further analyze the stability of the optimal policy under different $V$.

Figs. \ref{V_0_len} - \ref{V_200_len} \hl{illustrates the average queue backlog of three types of tasks under different policies and $V$. We can see that under different $V$ values, the queue backlog of LySAC policy reaches a stable state. This is because the LySAC policy can allocate computing resources according to real-time demands, thus achieve a stable state of queue backlog. The queue backlogs of the four other policies are consistently smaller than that of the LySAC policy, which are due to the higher CPU frequencies utilized.
%, thereby indicating the LySAC policy's ability to maintain queue stability even under low CPU frequencies.
As the value of $V$ increases, the queue backlog of LySAC policy decreases. This because as $V$ increases, LySAC policy emphasizes more stability, necessitating higher CPU frequencies to process the tasks.
%Conversely, the average queue backlogs of the other policies remain relatively unchanged, as they exhibit minimal variations in CPU frequency.
The EAEO policy yields the smallest queue backlog, as it utilizes the entire CPU frequency to process tasks. The average queue backlog of HGGA policy is roughly the same as that of the HGRA policy, because both employ the same decision-making approach in allocating CPU frequencies. The PSO policy performs relatively poorly compared to the EAEO, HGGA, and HGRA policies when operating at higher CPU frequencies, this is because PSO does not allocate CPU frequencies properly to different types of tasks, resulting in a large queue backlog despite using a high total CPU frequency.}

Fig. \ref{fig_CPU_3D} \hl{illustrates the box plots of the CPU frequencies allocated by various policies for processing 3D games across all time steps under $V$. We focus only on 3D games because this task demands the highest workload, and the CPU frequency allocated for processing 3D games often affects the queue stability. From the figure, it can be observed that the PSO policy exhibits the highest degree of dispersion in CPU frequency allocation, suggesting that the PSO policy fails to make a reasonable allocation of CPU frequencies based on queue backlog, latency, and utility.
%Additionally, the HGGA policy has a higher dispersion than the HGRA policy, which also explains why the HGGA policy has a longer queue backlog than the HGRA policy.
LySAC policy's CPU frequency allocation is more concentrated and has a lower mean value compared to other policies under the same $V$, indicating that the LySAC policy is more stable and can effectively make an optimal allocation based on actual queue length, delay and utility.}

%Figs. \ref{V_0_delay}-\ref{V_200_delay} \hl{depict the relationship between the violation probability and the average delay upper bound for three types of tasks under various policies and values of $V$. Here, the violation probability is calculated as the percentage of instances where the delay exceeds the upper bound. From the figures, we can observe that LySAC policies ensures low latency requirements, where the probability of violating a delay greater than 30ms is below 0.01. This validates the efficacy of our policy. EAEO, HGRA, and HGGA policies are also capable of ensuring low latency requirements. This is attributed to the fact that EAEO and HGRA policies achieve this performance by using resources. HGGA policy exhibits the best performance, which is due to its technique of offloading tasks using only one method, allowing it a high probability of not having other tasks competing for communication resources. On the other hand, HGGA policy utilizes a comparatively larger amount of computing resources. PSO policy fails to ensure low latency requirements and also consumes a significant amount of average resources. This indicates that the performance of PSO policy in handling such task offloading for ultra-reliable low-latency requirements is not satisfactory.}


Figs. \ref{V_0_delay}-\ref{V_200_delay} \hl{depict the relationship between the violation probability and the average delay upper bound for three types of tasks under various policies and $V$. Here, the violation probability is calculated as the percentage of instances where the delay exceeds the upper bound. From the figures, we can observe that LySAC policies ensures low latency requirements, where the probability of violating a delay greater than 30ms is below 0.01. This validates the efficacy of our policy. EAEO, HGRA, and HGGA policies are also capable of ensuring low latency requirements. This is attributed to they using more resources. HGGA policy exhibits the best performance, which is due to it use only one communication technology to offloading, allowing it a high probability of not having other tasks competing for communication resources. PSO policy fails to ensure low latency requirements. This indicates that the performance of PSO policy in handling such task offloading for ultra-reliable low-latency requirements is not satisfactory.}

Fig. \ref{performance_len} \hl{depicts the variation in the average delay upper bound as a function of the average number of tasks for all policies when $V = 200$. From the figure, with the increase in the average number of tasks, the average delay upper bound for HGGA increases rapidly, this because HGGA uses only one communication technology for task offloading. In contrast, the LySAC policy maintains commendable latency performance even with a higher number of tasks, efficiently harnessing the advantages of three communication technologies. The EAEO and HGRA policies have comparable and slightly inferior latency performance; this is partly due to the trade-off between resources for latency performance, and partly indicative that the offloading policy of the HGRA policy is more aligned with the EAEO policy.}
\vspace{-0.5cm}
\section{Conclusions}
\label{conclusion_chapter}
%\vspace{-0.1cm}
In this paper, we considered a integrated VEC with three kinds of communication
technologies and proposed a resource allocation policy based on SAC to minimize the system utility while guaranteeing its URLLC requirement. We derived the delay upper bound of offloading tasks based on the SNC theory, and we adopted the Lyapunov optimization to transform the ultra reliability constraint into an short-term decision constraint and reformulated the optimization problem. Finally, we employed the DRL to obtain the optimal allocation policy to the optimization problem. Extensive simulation results demonstrated that the proposed VEC design and its resource allocation policy can minimize the system utility while satisfying URLLC requirement.
\vspace{-0.4cm}
